[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] Many applications use **JSON Web Tokens** (JWT) to allow the client to indicate its identity for further exchange after authentication.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] JWTs are used to carry information related to the identity and characteristics (claims) of a client.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] This information is signed by the server to ensure it has not been tampered with after being sent to the client.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] This prevents an attacker from modifying the identity or characteristics — for example, changing the role from a simple user to an admin or altering the client's login.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] The token is created during authentication (it is issued upon successful authentication) and is verified by the server before any processing.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] Applications use the token to allow a client to present what is essentially an "identity card" to the server.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] The server can then securely verify the token's validity and integrity.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] This approach is stateless and portable, meaning it works across different client and server technologies, and over various transport channels — although HTTP is the most commonly used.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] This cheatsheet provides tips to prevent common security issues when using JSON Web Tokens (JWT) with Java.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] The tips presented in this article are part of a Java project that was created to show the correct way to handle creation and validation of JSON Web Tokens.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] You can find the Java project here, it uses the official JWT library.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] In the rest of the article, the term **token** refers to the **JSON Web Tokens** (JWT).
