[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] This attack occurs when a token has been intercepted/stolen by an attacker and they use it to gain access to the system using targeted user identity.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] One way to prevent this is by adding a "user context" to the token.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] Avoid using IP addresses as part of the context.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] IP addresses can change during a single session due to legitimate reasons — for example, when a user accesses the application on a mobile device and switches network providers.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] Additionally, IP tracking can raise concerns related to GDPR compliance in the EU.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] During token validation, if the received token does not contain the correct context (e.g., if it is being replayed by an attacker), it must be rejected.
