[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] The denylist approach described above is typically operated by the relying party (resource server) — it works well when the audience maintains its own revocation state close to where tokens are validated.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] However, in some deployments the issuer needs to centrally broadcast revocation state to multiple relying parties without requiring each one to maintain its own denylist.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] For this use case, the IETF Token Status List (TSL) draft defines a scalable, issuer-maintained revocation mechanism.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] TSL is used in SD-JWT Verifiable Credentials and other high-scale deployments where a single issuer serves many relying parties.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] Consult the TSL draft for implementation guidance when issuer-side revocation is required.
[src:jwt-security-pitfalls/json-web-token-cheat-sheet] This attack occurs when an attacker has access to a token (or a set of tokens) and extracts information stored in it (the contents of JWTs are base64 encoded, but is not encrypted by default) in order to obtain information about the system.
